<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-linear-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Linear Functions</title>
  <p>
    There are many ways to write the equation of a line. For instance, the equations <m>y = 3x - 2</m>, <m>3x-y = 2</m>, 
    and <m>y-1 = 3(x-1)</m> all describe the linear function graphed below.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
    <image width="60%">
      <prefigure label="prefigure-line-0" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
        <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
          <definition>
            f(x) = 3*x-2
          </definition>
          <coordinates bbox="[-2,-8,3,8]">
            <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
            <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
          </coordinates>
        </diagram>
      </prefigure>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    We'll focus on two often-used conventions for how to write the equation of a line: <term>Point-Slope Form</term> 
    and <term>Slope-Intercept Form</term>.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-point-slope-form">
    <title>Point-Slope Form</title>

    <p>
      This form is good if you just want to write the equation of a line and don't mind if it's messy. Here are the steps
      for writing the equation of a line in point-slope form.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find one point on the line, <m>(a,b)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find the slope of the line, <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plug the point and slope into the equation
          <md>
            y-b = m(x-a)
          </md>
          In this equation, <m>a</m>,<m>b</m>, and <m>m</m> will be numbers that you plug in, and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>
          will remain as variables.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <example><title>Equation in Point-Slope Form From Graph</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation for the given line. Write your answer in point-slope form.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
          <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-line" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = 3*x-5
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-1,-6,5,5]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              First we need to choose a point on the line. I will choose the point <m>(a,b)=(2,1)</m>, but you could use other
              points on the graph instead, like <m>(3,4)</m> or <m>(1,-2)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Using two points on the graph, we need to find the slope. I will use the points <m>(2,1)</m> and <m>(3,4)</m>.
              With these, I compute the slope.
              <md>
                m = \frac{1-4}{2-3} = \frac{-3}{-1} = 3
              </md>
              You may use different points from the graph to compute the slope, but no matter which points you choose, 
              you should get <m>m=3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Plugging this point and slope into the formula for Point-Slope Form, we get
              <md>
                y-1 = 3(x-2)
              </md>
              If you choose a different point in Step 1, it will result in a different but equivalent answer. For example,
              if you use the point <m>(3,4)</m>, your answer will be <md>y-4 = 3(x-3)</md>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example><title>Equation in Point-Slope Form From Data</title>
     <statement>
      Find the equation, in point-slope form, of the line that goes through the point <m>(-2, -4)</m> and has a slope
      of <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>.
     </statement>
     <solution>
      <p>
        In this example, we are given the point <m>(a,b) = (-2, -4)</m> and the slope <m>m = \frac{1}{4}</m>. We plug them
        into the formula for Point-Slope Form, we get
        <md>
          y - (-4) = \frac{1}{4}(x - (-2))
        </md>
        which simplifies to become
        <md>
          y+4 = \frac{1}{4}(x+2)  
        </md> 
      </p>
     </solution>  
    </example>

    <example><title>You Try It!</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation for the given line. Write your answer in point-slope form.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
          <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-line-2" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = (4/5)*x+(13/5)
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-3,-1,4,6]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          If you use the point <m>(-2,1)</m>, the answer is <m>y-1 = \frac{4}{5}(x+2)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you use the point <m>(3,5)</m>, the answer is <m>y-5 = \frac{4}{5}(x-3)</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      </example>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-slope-intercept-form">
    <title>Slope-Intercept Form</title>
    
    <p>
      If you want the equation of a line to match function notation (<m>y</m> or <m>f(x)</m> on one side by itself), then
      you should use <term>Slope-Intercept Form</term> to write the equation of your line. As a bonus, as the name suggests,
      this form encodes important geometric information about the graph of the line, namely its slope and <m>y</m>-intercept.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-slope-intercept-form">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>slope-intercept form</term> of the equation of the line with slope <m>m</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept
          <m>b</m> is
          <md>
            y = mx+b
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Recall that the <m>y</m>-intercept of a graph describe where the graph crosses the <m>y</m>-axis. So when we say
      that the <m>y</m>-intercept of a graph is <m>b</m>, that means the graph crosses the <m>y</m>-axis at the point
      <m>(0,b)</m>. A linear function will always have a unique <m>y</m>-intercept. Can you explain why? If not, review
      the Vertical Line Test.
    </p>

    <p>
      Because the slope and <m>y</m>-intercept of a line are unique, the slope-intercept form of the equation for a line
      has the added benefit that it is unique, too. That is, there is only one way to write the slope-intercept form of 
      the equation for a given line, so in our examples and exercises, we will all get the same answers.
    </p>

    <p>
      The steps for writing the equation of a line in slope-intercept form based on its graph will depend on whether or
     not the <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>b</m>, is clear from the graph.
    </p>

    <p>
      If you can tell the <m>y</m>-intercept by looking at the graph:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Find the <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>b</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use two points on the graph to calculate the slope, <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plug <m>b</m> and <m>m</m> into the equation <md>y = mx+b.</md>
          In this equation, <m>m</m> and <m>b</m> will be numbers that you plug in and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> will remain
          as variables.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      If you can't tell the exact value of the <m>y</m>-intercept by looking at the graph:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use two points on the graph to calculate the slope, <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Choose one point from the graph, <m>(a,b)</m>, and plug it into Point-Slope Form:
          <md>
            y-b = m(x-a)
          </md>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
         Solve the equation for <m>y</m> and simplify so that it is written in the form <m>y = mx+b</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <example><title>Equation in Slope-Intercept Form From Graph</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation for the given line. Write your answer in slope-intercept form.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
          <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-line-3" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = (-2/3)*x+2
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-1,-1,4,3]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          From this graph, we can see that the line crosses the <m>y</m>-axis at the point <m>(0,2)</m>, so the <m>y</m>-
          intercept is <m>b=2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the slope, choose two points from the graph. For instance, we can use the points <m>(0,2)</m> and 
          <m>(3,0)</m>. Then the slope is
          <md>
            m = \frac{0-2}{3-0} = -\frac{2}{3}
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Plugging the slope and intercept into the formula <m>y = mx+b</m>, our answer is
          <md>
            y = -\frac{2}{3}x+2
          </md>    
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

        <example><title>Equation in Slope-Intercept Form From Graph</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation for the given line. Write your answer in point-slope form.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
          <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-line-4" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = (1/3)*x+(1/3)
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-2,-1,4,2]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For this graph, it's not clear what the exact value of the <m>y</m>-intercept is. I can tell it is between 0 
          and <m>0.5</m>, maybe <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> or <m>0.3</m>. We will need to use the second method to write the
          equation in slope-intercept form.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let's start by finding the slope. For this, we need two points on the line. We can use <m>(-1,0)</m> and 
          <m>(2,1)</m>. The slope is
          <md>
            m = \frac{1-0}{2-(-1)} = \frac{1}{3}
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Choose one of these points, say <m>(-1,0)</m> to write the equation in point-slope form:
          <md>
            y - 0 = \frac{1}{3}(x+1)
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Simplifying, we get our answer:
          <md>
            y = \frac{1}{3}x+\frac{1}{3}
          </md>
          From this, we can see that the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>b = \frac{1}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>


     <example><title>Equation in Slope-Intercept Form From Data</title>
     <statement>
      Find the equation, in slope-intercept form, of the line that goes through the point <m>(2, 7)</m> and has a slope
      of <m>m = \frac{1}{2}</m>.
     </statement>
     <solution>
      <p>
        To get an answer, we will plug the information given into point-slope form, rearrange to get <m>y</m> by itself,
        and simplify.
        <md>
          <mrow> y-7 \amp = \frac{1}{2}(x-2) </mrow>
          <mrow> y-7 \amp = \frac{1}{2}x - 1 </mrow>
          <mrow> y \amp = \frac{1}{2}x + 6 </mrow>
        </md>
        So our final answer is <m>y = \frac{1}{2}x+6</m>.
      </p>
     </solution>  
    </example>

    <example><title>Equation in Slope-Intercept Form From Data</title>
     <statement>
      <p>
      Other than convenience, there's no reason to expect that the slope and intercept of a linear function will work out
      to be "nice" numbers. Let's look at an example where the numbers are messier.
      </p>
      <p>
      Find the equation, in slope-intercept form, of the line that goes through the point <m>(-1, -3)</m> and has a slope
      of <m>m = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>.
      </p>
     </statement>
     <solution>
      <p>
        To get an answer, we'll follow the same steps as usual: plug the information given into point-slope form, 
        rearrange to get <m>y</m> by itself, and simplify.
        <md>
          <mrow> y+3 \amp = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(x+1) </mrow>
          <mrow> y+3 \amp = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} </mrow>
          <mrow> y \amp = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} - 3 </mrow>
          <mrow> y \amp = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x - \left(3+ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right) </mrow>
        </md>
        So our final answer is <m>y = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}x - \left(3+ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)</m>.
      </p>
     </solution>  
    </example>

    <example><title>You Try It!</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the equation, in slope-intercept form, of the line that goes through the point <m>(4, 1)</m> and has a slope
          of <m>m = \frac{3}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>y = \frac{3}{2}x - 5</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      </example>

  </subsection>
</section>